Bring a large #pot{} of @salted water{} to a boil. Wash and dry all produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Peel and mince
@ginger{1%thumb} and @garlic{1%clove}. Roughly chop @peanuts{1/2%ounce}.

In a #small bowl{}, whisk together @Szechuan paste{2%tablespoon}, @rice wine vinegar{5%teaspoon},
@cornstarch{1%tablespoon}, half the @sesame oil{1/2%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest
later), @sugar{1%tablespoon}, and @water{3/4%cup}.

> 4 SERVINGS: Use 2 TBSP sugar and 1 1/2 cups water.

Heat remaining @sesame oil{1/2%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat.
Add @ground pork{10%ounce}, scallion whites, ginger, and garlic. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until pork is browned
and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Once water is boiling, stir @ramen noodles{6%ounce} into pot. Cook until tender,
~{1-2%minutes}. Drain and rinse under cold water. Set aside.

> Toss noodles with a drizzle of oil after rinsing to prevent sticking.

Stir @coleslaw mix{4%ounce} into pan with pork mixture; cook until softened,
~{1%minute}.

Reduce heat to medium, then add ramen noodles. Stir in sauce and toss until
everything is thoroughly coated, ~{1-2%minutes}. If sauce is too thick,
add a splash of water. Taste and season with salt and pepper. Turn off heat.

Divide between #bowls{}. Top with scallion greens and peanuts. Serve.

> If your pan isn't large enough, transfer everything back into pot used to cook
> noodles for tossing.